<chapter>
  <title> Proteus Chpt 9 Questions </title>

  <exercise label="chkpt-sequences-02">
    <title>Range of a sequence</title>
    <statement>
      <p>
        Select all statements that correctly describe the <m>\text{range}</m> of a sequence <m>\{a_n\}</m>.
      </p>
    </statement>
    <choices randomize="yes">
      <choice correct="yes">
        <statement>
          <p>
            It is the set of all distinct values taken on by <m>a_n</m>.
          </p>
        </statement>
        <feedback>
          <p>
            The range collects values the sequence hits, ignoring how many times a value repeats.
          </p>
        </feedback>
      </choice>
      <choice>
        <statement>
          <p>
            It is the ordered list <m>a_1,a_2,a_3,\dots</m>.
          </p>
        </statement>
        <feedback>
          <p>
            The ordered list is the list of terms. The range is a set, so it ignores order and repetition.
          </p>
        </feedback>
      </choice>
      <choice correct="yes">
        <statement>
          <p>
            If <m>a_n</m> repeats values, those repeated values appear only once in the range.
          </p>
        </statement>
        <feedback>
          <p>
            Repetition does not create new elements of the range.
          </p>
        </feedback>
      </choice>
      <choice>
        <statement>
          <p>
            The range must be infinite because the sequence has infinitely many terms.
          </p>
        </statement>
        <feedback>
          <p>
            A sequence can take only finitely many distinct values (for example, alternating between two numbers).
          </p>
        </feedback>
      </choice>
      <choice correct="yes">
        <statement>
          <p>
            The range can be finite even though the domain <m>\mathbb{N}</m> is infinite.
          </p>
        </statement>
        <feedback>
          <p>
            What matters is how many distinct outputs occur, not how many inputs there are.
          </p>
        </feedback>
      </choice>
      <choice>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Changing the order of the terms changes the range.
          </p>
        </statement>
        <feedback>
          <p>
            The range is a set of values, so order does not matter; reordering terms does not change which values occur.
          </p>
        </feedback>
      </choice>
    </choices>
  </exercise>

  <exercise label="chkpt-sequences-07">
    <title>Using the function–sequence limit link</title>
    <statement>
      <p>
        Suppose you find a function <m>f(x)</m> with <m>f(n)=a_n</m> for all <m>n\in\mathbb{N}</m>, but the limit <m>\displaystyle\lim_{x\to\infty} f(x)</m> does not exist. What can you conclude about <m>\displaystyle\lim_{n\to\infty} a_n</m>?
      </p>
    </statement>
    <choices randomize="yes">
      <choice>
        <statement>
          <p>
            The sequence limit does not exist.
          </p>
        </statement>
        <feedback>
          <p>
            A non-existent limit for <m>f(x)</m> over the reals does not force the integer-input subsequence <m>f(n)</m> to behave the same way.
          </p>
        </feedback>
      </choice>
      <choice correct="yes">
        <statement>
          <p>
            No definite conclusion: the sequence limit may exist or may not exist.
          </p>
        </statement>
        <feedback>
          <p>
            It is possible for <m>f(x)</m> to oscillate on real inputs while <m>f(n)</m> behaves more simply on integer inputs (for example, a cosine function can do this).
          </p>
        </feedback>
      </choice>
      <choice>
        <statement>
          <p>
            The sequence must diverge to <m>\infty</m>.
          </p>
        </statement>
        <feedback>
          <p>
            Diverging to <m>\infty</m> is a specific type of divergence; “no limit for <m>f(x)</m>” does not imply unbounded growth of <m>a_n</m>.
          </p>
        </feedback>
      </choice>
      <choice>
        <statement>
          <p>
            The sequence must converge, but you cannot find the value.
          </p>
        </statement>
        <feedback>
          <p>
            The theorem only gives implications in one direction: a limit for <m>f(x)</m> implies a limit for <m>a_n</m>, not the other way around.
          </p>
        </feedback>
      </choice>
    </choices>
  </exercise>

  <exercise label="chkpt-sequences-08">
    <title>Which idea fits the sequence?</title>
    <statement>
      <p>
        Match each sequence with the most appropriate conclusion or tool suggested by the narrative.
      </p>
    </statement>
    <feedback>
      <p>
        Different sequences call for different “first looks”: extending to a familiar function, checking for oscillation, using absolute values, or recognizing unbounded growth.
      </p>
    </feedback>
    <cardsort>
      <match>
        <premise><m>\ds a_n=\frac{3n^2-2n+1}{n^2-1000}</m></premise>
        <response>Extend to a rational function <m>f(x)</m> and use a limit at infinity to find the sequence limit.</response>
      </match>
      <match>
        <premise><m>\ds a_n=\cos(2\pi n)</m></premise>
        <response>Recognize that every term equals <m>1</m>, so the sequence converges to <m>1</m>.</response>
      </match>
      <match>
        <premise><m>\ds a_n=\cos(n)</m></premise>
        <response>Use oscillation to argue the terms get close to both <m>1</m> and <m>-1</m> infinitely often, so no limit exists.</response>
      </match>
      <match>
        <premise><m>\ds a_n=\frac{(-1)^n}{n}</m></premise>
        <response>Use <m>\abs{a_n}=\frac1n\to 0</m> and conclude <m>a_n\to 0</m> (Absolute Value Theorem idea).</response>
      </match>
      <match>
        <premise><m>\ds a_n=2^n</m></premise>
        <response>Show that for every <m>M&gt;0</m>, terms eventually exceed <m>M</m>, so the sequence diverges to <m>\infty</m>.</response>
      </match>
    </cardsort>
  </exercise>

  <exercise label="chkpt-sequences-10">
    <title>Convergent vs. bounded</title>
    <statement>
      <p>
        Which statement is always true?
      </p>
    </statement>
    <choices randomize="yes">
      <choice>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Every bounded sequence converges.
          </p>
        </statement>
        <feedback>
          <p>
            A sequence can stay within bounds and still fail to settle to one value (oscillation is a common reason).
          </p>
        </feedback>
      </choice>
      <choice correct="yes">
        <statement>
          <p>
            Every convergent sequence is bounded.
          </p>
        </statement>
        <feedback>
          <p>
            If the terms get arbitrarily close to a finite limit, then all but finitely many terms lie in a small interval around that limit, and the remaining finitely many terms can also be bounded.
          </p>
        </feedback>
      </choice>
      <choice>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Every divergent sequence is unbounded.
          </p>
        </statement>
        <feedback>
          <p>
            Divergence can happen even when the terms remain between two numbers (for instance, by oscillating without approaching a single value).
          </p>
        </feedback>
      </choice>
      <choice>
        <statement>
          <p>
            If a sequence is unbounded, then it must diverge to <m>\infty</m>.
          </p>
        </statement>
        <feedback>
          <p>
            “Unbounded” allows growth toward <m>\infty</m>, toward <m>-\,\infty</m>, or even behavior that escapes in both directions.
          </p>
        </feedback>
      </choice>
    </choices>
  </exercise>

  <exercise label="chkpt-sequences-cardsort-01"><title>Sequence vocabulary</title>
    <statement>
      <p>
      Match each term or notation to its meaning.
      </p>
    </statement>
    <feedback>
      <p>
      A sequence is a function on <m>\mathbb{N}</m>. The words “term,” “domain,” and “range” describe inputs, outputs, and how we talk about them.
      </p>
    </feedback>
    <cardsort>
      <match>
      <premise>Domain of a sequence</premise>
      <response>The set of inputs, namely the natural numbers <m>1,2,3,\dots</m>.</response>
      </match>
      <match>
      <premise>Range of a sequence</premise>
      <response>The set of all distinct values that occur among <m>a_1,a_2,a_3,\dots</m>.</response>
      </match>
      <match>
      <premise>Term <m>a_4</m></premise>
      <response>The value of the sequence at <m>n=4</m>, i.e. <m>a(4)</m>.</response>
      </match>
      <match>
      <premise>Notation <m>\{a_n\}</m></premise>
      <response>The entire sequence (the list of terms produced by <m>a(n)</m>).</response>
      </match>
      <match>
      <premise>Factorial <m>n!</m></premise>
      <response>The product <m>n(n-1)(n-2)\cdots 2\cdot 1</m>, with <m>0!=1</m>.</response>
      </match>
    </cardsort>
  </exercise>

