  <!-- CHECKPOINT QUESTION 3: After Definition 8.1.3 (def_seq_limit) -->
  <!-- Tests conceptual understanding of limit definition using epsilon -->
  <exercise label="chkpt-seq-limit-concept"><title>Understanding Limits of Sequences</title>
    <statement>
      <p>
      Which of the following best describes what it means for a sequence <m>\{a_n\}</m> to have limit <m>L</m>?
      </p>
    </statement>
    <choices randomize="yes">
      <choice>
      <statement>
        <p>
        Every term of the sequence equals <m>L</m>.
        </p>
      </statement>
      <feedback>
        <p>
        This is too restrictive. A sequence can converge to <m>L</m> even if no term actually equals <m>L</m>, as long as the terms get arbitrarily close to <m>L</m>.
        </p>
      </feedback>
      </choice>
      <choice>
      <statement>
        <p>
        The terms of the sequence get closer to <m>L</m>, but never reach it.
        </p>
      </statement>
      <feedback>
        <p>
        This is close, but not quite right. The terms can actually equal <m>L</m> sometimes—the key is that they eventually stay arbitrarily close to <m>L</m>.
        </p>
      </feedback>
      </choice>
      <choice correct="yes">
      <statement>
        <p>
        For any <m>b \ne L</m>, all terms past some point will be closer to <m>L</m> than <m>b</m>.
        </p>
      </statement>
      <feedback>
        <p>
        Excellent! This captures the essence of the <m>\varepsilon</m>-<m>N</m> definition:
        </p>

        <tabular>
          <row>
            <cell>Given any <m>\varepsilon &gt; 0</m></cell><cell><m>\leftarrow</m></cell><cell><em><q>distance between <m>L</m> and <m>b</m></q></em></cell>
          </row>
          <row>
            <cell>there exists an <m>N</m></cell><cell><m>\leftarrow</m></cell><cell><em><q>some point</q></em></cell>
          </row>
          <row>
            <cell>such that <m>|a_n - L| &lt; \varepsilon</m></cell><cell><m>\leftarrow</m></cell><cell><em><q><m>a_{N}, a_{N+1}, a_{N+2}, \ldots</m> are closer to <m>L</m> than <m>b</m></q></em></cell>
          </row>
          <row>
            <cell>for all <m>n &gt; N</m></cell><cell><m>\leftarrow</m></cell><cell><em><q>for all terms past some point</q></em></cell>
          </row>
          <row><cell><m/></cell></row>
        </tabular>

      </feedback>
      </choice>
      <choice>
      <statement>
        <p>
        The average of all terms in the sequence equals <m>L</m>.
        </p>
      </statement>
      <feedback>
        <p>
        This describes a different concept (Cesàro summation). Limits are about the eventual behavior of terms, not their average.
        </p>
      </feedback>
      </choice>
    </choices>
  </exercise>

  <!-- CHECKPOINT QUESTION 4: After Theorem 8.1.2 (thm_seq_limit) -->
  <!-- Tests ability to apply the theorem connecting function and sequence limits -->
  <exercise label="chkpt-seq-function-limit"><title>Connecting Function and Sequence Limits</title>
    <statement>
      <p>
      Consider the function <m>f(x) = \frac{3x^2+5x}{x^2+1}</m>. If we know that <m>\lim\limits_{x\to\infty} f(x) = 3</m>, what can we conclude about the sequence <m>\{a_n\} = \left\{\frac{3n^2+5n}{n^2+1}\right\}</m>?
      </p>
    </statement>
    <choices randomize="yes">
      <choice>
      <statement>
        <p>
        We cannot conclude anything about <m>\lim\limits_{n\to\infty} a_n</m>.
        </p>
      </statement>
      <feedback>
        <p>
        Actually, we can! Since <m>f(n) = a_n</m> for all positive integers <m>n</m>, Theorem 8.1.2 allows us to draw a conclusion.
        </p>
      </feedback>
      </choice>
      <choice>
      <statement>
        <p>
        <m>\lim\limits_{n\to\infty} a_n</m> might equal 3, but we need more information.
        </p>
      </statement>
      <feedback>
        <p>
        We actually have enough information. Check Theorem 8.1.2 about the relationship between function limits and sequence limits.
        </p>
      </feedback>
      </choice>
      <choice correct="yes">
      <statement>
        <p>
        <m>\lim\limits_{n\to\infty} a_n = 3</m>
        </p>
      </statement>
      <feedback>
        <p>
        Correct! By Theorem 8.1.2, if <m>\lim\limits_{x\to\infty} f(x) = L</m> and <m>f(n) = a_n</m>, then <m>\lim\limits_{n\to\infty} a_n = L</m>. This theorem is extremely useful for evaluating sequence limits!
        </p>
      </feedback>
      </choice>
      <choice>
      <statement>
        <p>
        The sequence diverges.
        </p>
      </statement>
      <feedback>
        <p>
        No—since the corresponding function limit exists and equals 3, the sequence converges to 3 by Theorem 8.1.2.
        </p>
      </feedback>
      </choice>
    </choices>
  </exercise>

  <!-- CHECKPOINT QUESTION 5: After Example 8.1.4 (ex_seq4) -->
  <!-- Multiple-answer question about convergence/divergence properties -->
  <exercise label="chkpt-seq-converge-properties"><title>Convergence and Divergence Properties</title>
    <statement>
      <p>
      Which of the following statements are TRUE?
      </p>
    </statement>
    <choices randomize="yes">
      <choice correct="yes">
      <statement>
        <p>
        If <m>\lim\limits_{x\to\infty} f(x)</m> does not exist, the sequence <m>\{f(n)\}</m> might still converge.
        </p>
      </statement>
      <feedback>
        <p>
        Correct! The example <m>f(x) = \cos(2\pi x)</m> oscillates as a function, but <m>\{f(n)\} = \{\cos(2\pi n)\} = \{1, 1, 1, \ldots\}</m> converges to 1.
        </p>
      </feedback>
      </choice>
      <choice>
      <statement>
        <p>
        A sequence that oscillates between two values must diverge.
        </p>
      </statement>
      <feedback>
        <p>
        This is false. While the sequence <m>\{4 + (-1)^n\}</m> from Example 8.1.4 does oscillate and diverge, a sequence could oscillate between values that get closer together and still converge (like <m>\{(-1)^n/n\}</m> converging to 0).
        </p>
      </feedback>
      </choice>
      <choice correct="yes">
      <statement>
        <p>
        If <m>\lim\limits_{n\to\infty} |a_n| = 0</m>, then <m>\lim\limits_{n\to\infty} a_n = 0</m>.
        </p>
      </statement>
      <feedback>
        <p>
        Correct! This is the Absolute Value Theorem (Theorem 8.1.4). If the absolute values approach 0, then the terms themselves must approach 0.
        </p>
      </feedback>
      </choice>
      <choice>
      <statement>
        <p>
        Every convergent sequence must be monotonic.
        </p>
      </statement>
      <feedback>
        <p>
        This is false. The sequence <m>\{(-1)^n/n\}</m> converges to 0 but is not monotonic—it alternates between positive and negative values.
        </p>
      </feedback>
      </choice>
      <choice correct="yes">
      <statement>
        <p>
        We can use L'Hôpital's Rule to evaluate some sequence limits.
        </p>
      </statement>
      <feedback>
        <p>
        Correct! When we can write <m>a_n = f(n)</m> for some function <m>f</m>, we can use L'Hôpital's Rule on <m>\lim\limits_{x\to\infty} f(x)</m> and then apply Theorem 8.1.2.
        </p>
      </feedback>
      </choice>
    </choices>
  </exercise>

  <!-- CHECKPOINT QUESTION 6: After Definition 8.1.7 (def_bounded) -->
  <!-- Matching exercise connecting sequences to boundedness properties -->
  <exercise label="chkpt-seq-bounded-matching"><title>Identifying Bounded Sequences</title>
    <statement>
      <p>
      Match each sequence to its boundedness property.
      </p>
    </statement>
    <feedback>
      <p>
      Remember: bounded means both bounded above and below; bounded above means there's a ceiling but possibly no floor; bounded below means there's a floor but possibly no ceiling.
      </p>
    </feedback>
    <cardsort>
      <match>
        <premise><m>\left\{\frac{\sin(n)}{n}\right\}</m></premise>
        <premise><m>\left\{\frac{(-1)^n \cdot n}{n+1}\right\}</m></premise>
        <response>Bounded</response>
      </match>
      <match>
        <premise><m>\{n^2\}</m></premise>
        <response>Bounded below only</response>
      </match>
      <match>
        <premise><m>\{-n^3\}</m></premise>
        <response>Bounded above only</response>
      </match>
      <match>
        <premise><m>\{n\sin(n)\}</m></premise>
        <response>Unbounded</response>
      </match>
    </cardsort>
  </exercise>

  <!-- CHECKPOINT QUESTION 7: After Theorem 8.1.8 (thm_converge_bounded) -->
  <!-- True/False about the converse of the theorem -->
  <exercise label="chkpt-seq-bounded-converse"><title>Bounded Sequences and Convergence</title>
    <statement correct="no">
      <p>
      True or False: If a sequence <m>\{a_n\}</m> is bounded, then it must converge.
      </p>
    </statement>
    <feedback>
      <p>
      False! Theorem 8.1.8 states that convergent sequences are bounded, but the converse is not true. A counterexample is <m>\{(-1)^n\}</m>, which is bounded (all terms are either 1 or -1) but diverges because it oscillates. To guarantee convergence, a bounded sequence must also be <em>monotonic</em> (Theorem 8.1.10).
      </p>
    </feedback>
  </exercise>

  <!-- CHECKPOINT QUESTION 8: After Definition 8.1.9 (def_monotonic) -->
  <!-- Clickable area question about monotonicity -->
  <exercise label="chkpt-seq-monotonic-identify"><title>Identifying Monotonic Behavior</title>
    <statement>
      <p>
      Click on all sequences below that are monotonically increasing.
      </p>
    </statement>
    <areas>
      <p>
        <area><m>\left\{\frac{n}{n+1}\right\}</m></area><m>,\quad</m>
        <area correct="no"><m>\{(-1)^n \cdot n\}</m></area><m>,\quad</m>
        <area><m>\left\{1 - \frac{1}{n}\right\}</m></area><m>,\quad</m>
        <area correct="no"><m>\left\{\frac{n^2-9}{n^2-10n+26}\right\}</m></area><m>,\quad</m>
        <area correct="no"><m>\{3 - 2^n\}</m></area>
      </p>
    </areas>
    <feedback>
      <p>
      A sequence is monotonically increasing if <m>a_n \leq a_{n+1}</m> for all <m>n</m>. Check this by computing <m>a_{n+1} - a_n</m>: if it's always non-negative, the sequence is increasing. Note that <m>\{(-1)^n \cdot n\}</m> alternates in sign, <m>\left\{\frac{n^2-9}{n^2-10n+26}\right\}</m> increases then decreases (see Example 8.1.7c), and <m>\{3-2^n\}</m> is <em>decreasing</em> since the <m>2^n</m> term grows.
      </p>
    </feedback>
  </exercise>

  <!-- CHECKPOINT QUESTION 10: After Theorem 8.1.10 (thm_monotonic_converge) -->
  <!-- Comprehensive question applying the Monotonic Convergence Theorem -->
  <exercise label="chkpt-seq-monotonic-converge"><title>Applying the Monotonic Convergence Theorem</title>
    <statement>
      <p>
      Consider the sequence <m>\{a_n\}</m> where <m>a_1 = 2</m> and <m>a_{n+1} = \sqrt{2 + a_n}</m> for all <m>n \geq 1</m>. Suppose we can show that:
      </p>
      <p>
      (i) <m>a_n &lt; 3</m> for all <m>n</m>, and
      </p>
      <p>
      (ii) <m>a_{n+1} > a_n</m> for all <m>n</m>.
      </p>
      <p>
      What can we conclude?
      </p>
    </statement>
    <choices randomize="yes">
      <choice>
      <statement>
        <p>
        The sequence might converge or might diverge—we need more information.
        </p>
      </statement>
      <feedback>
        <p>
        We actually have enough information! We know the sequence is both monotonic (increasing) and bounded (above by 3, below by 2).
        </p>
      </feedback>
      </choice>
      <choice correct="yes">
      <statement>
        <p>
        The sequence must converge to some limit <m>L</m> where <m>2 \leq L \leq 3</m>.
        </p>
      </statement>
      <feedback>
        <p>
        Excellent! By Theorem 8.1.10, a monotonically increasing sequence that is bounded above must converge. Since all terms satisfy <m>2 \leq a_n &lt; 3</m>, the limit must satisfy <m>2 \leq L \leq 3</m>. (In fact, by taking limits in the recursion relation, we can show <m>L = 2</m>!)
        </p>
      </feedback>
      </choice>
      <choice>
      <statement>
        <p>
        The sequence must converge to 3.
        </p>
      </statement>
      <feedback>
        <p>
        While the theorem guarantees convergence, it doesn't tell us the exact value of the limit. We know the limit is at most 3, but it could be less.
        </p>
      </feedback>
      </choice>
      <choice>
      <statement>
        <p>
        The sequence must diverge to infinity.
        </p>
      </statement>
      <feedback>
        <p>
        No—the sequence is bounded above by 3, so it cannot diverge to infinity. Check Theorem 8.1.10 about bounded monotonic sequences.
